Vice President Pence commemorated the 34th anniversary of the bombing of the U.S. and French Barracks in Beirut, Lebanon, where 241 U.S. service members and 58 French paratroopers were killed. General McMaster also highlighted the role of Hezbollah and its sponsor Iran in perpetuating terrorism and destabilizing the Middle East. Pence honored those who lost their lives and their families, and expressed confidence in the support of the Armed Forces under the current administration. He mentioned the increase in defense spending and the U.S.'s withdrawal from the Iran nuclear deal. Pence also noted the liberation of Raqqa, the self-proclaimed capital of ISIS, and pledged to eradicate terrorism under President Trump's leadership. The Vice President concluded by expressing gratitude to the families of the fallen and emphasizing their eternal remembrance.